body:
It seems like the input feed as a list misguides some existing logic into thinking that we are trying to create a sequence tensor and finally runs into this error message : "Either type_proto was null or it was not of sequence type" while performing some sanity check. 

@jywu-msft - Do we plan to support lists (and nested lists for multi-dimensional inputs) for the feeds in Python ?

> It seems like the input feed as a list misguides some existing logic into thinking that we are trying to create a sequence tensor and finally runs into this error message : "Either type_proto was null or it was not of sequence type" while performing some sanity check.
> 
> @jywu-msft - Do we plan to support lists (and nested lists for multi-dimensional inputs) for the feeds in Python ?

no, 
there are no plans to interpret python lists as anything other than onnx sequence.

python lists represent onnx sequences
python dicts to represent onnx maps. 
and onnx tensors are represented as numpy arrays.

issue.title: Support non-sequence tensor fed through as a python list

issue.body:
**Description**: Popular frameworks like Scikit support Python lists as feed types whereas ORT only accepts numpy arrays for tensors and a list of numpy arrays to support sequence tensor type in ONNX. This change is to support a list that is to be interpreted as just a tensor (and not a sequence tensor) when it is appropriate to do so.

**Motivation and Context**
Resolve #2733

body: @jywu-msft : Thanks for confirming. I actually already had the change to support the requested scenario. The PR can be disregarded if you feel the support is not required. It may help the OP or someone looking for similar support. Thanks.

> @jywu-msft : Thanks for confirming. I actually already had the change to support the requested scenario. The PR can be disregarded if you feel the support is not required. It may help the OP or someone looking for similar support. Thanks.

Thanks for the PR. I wasn't aware of any plans or requirements to support that scenario. We can re-consider it if there is a strong use-case.
My hesitation is mapping python list to multiple data types doesn't feel clean.

@jywu-msft: Thanks. There wasn't any plan or requirement. I just thought I would try and address this open issue which basically asks for this feature. I had the same apprehension because numpy array comes bound to a specific type whereas python list objects may basically contain anything and need to be handled with care. The logic in the PR basically tries to parse the provided list based on the type specified by the TypeProto for the specific input failing which, it throws. I see both sides to this - it does seem reasonable o support it especially if other popular frameworks like scikit support it, whereas numpy arrays do seem safer to handle for regular tensors (especially when ONNX supports an inherent sequence tensor type). Anyway, I ll keep the PR open in case, someone wants to use the logic. Thanks!
